annada reduplication and Taqbaylit of Chemini “floating prepositions” all being cases in point. Others have a typological focus, highlighting and attempting to explain striking patterns like the Final-over-Final Constraint or considering the predictions of particular theoretical approacesh (the movement theory of Control, multidominance, Distributed Morphology) in relation to structures that we do and don’t expect to be “possible linguistic structures”. Broader architectural questions also receive attention from various perspectives. This volume will be of interest to advanced students and researchers with interests in the externalisation of ling  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and general. 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aLinguistik. 4aSyntaktische. 4aTypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh  aLanguage Faculty.  aLanguage Structure.  aLinguistics Typology.1 aBendjaballah, Sabrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiberauer, Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiberauer, Theresa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBranchini, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecchetto, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCitko, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonati, Caterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowlie, Meaghan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGračanin-Yuksek, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaddad, Youssef A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator